        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000002816": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000002816",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-0bfa64 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-e8bee0 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"div1 c12\"><div class=\"fit\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\"><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000002701\">[3]</$link> The H.-So punctuation has been followed; but B. has been followed in understanding ‘<span class=\"ang\">gehwylcne</span>’ as object of ‘<span class=\"ang\">wíd-scofen (hæfde)</span>.’ Gr. construes ‘<span class=\"ang\">wéa</span>’ as nom abs.</div></div></div></div></div>"
        },
