        "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005049": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005049",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-0bfa64 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-e8bee0 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"div1 c12\"><div class=\"fit\"><div class=\"footnotes\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005050": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005050",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-0bfa64 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-e8bee0 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"div1 c12\"><div class=\"fit\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\"><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000004947\">[1]</$link> ‘<span class=\"ang\">Meodu-scencum</span>’ (1981) some would render ‘<i>with mead-pourers</i>.’ Translate then: <i>The daughter of Hæreth went through the building accompanied by mead-pourers</i>.</div></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005051": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005051",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-0bfa64 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-e8bee0 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"div1 c12\"><div class=\"fit\"><div class=\"footnotes\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005052": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005052",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-0bfa64 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-e8bee0 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"div1 c12\"><div class=\"fit\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\"><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000004977\">[2]</$link> See my note to <$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000004120\">1599</$link>, supra, and B. in P. and B. XII. 97.</div></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005053": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005053",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-0bfa64 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-e8bee0 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"div1 c12\"><div class=\"fit\"><div class=\"footnotes\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005054": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005054",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-0bfa64 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-e8bee0 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"div1 c12\"><div class=\"fit\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\"><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005001\">[3]</$link> For ‘<span class=\"ang\">fenne</span>,’ supplied by Grdtvg., B. suggests ‘<span class=\"ang\">fácne</span>’ (cf. Jul. 350). Accepting this, translate: <i>Who longest lives of the hated race, steeped in treachery</i>.</div></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005055": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005055",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-0bfa64 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-e8bee0 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"div1 c12\"><div class=\"fit\"><div class=\"footnotes\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005056": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005056",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-0bfa64 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-e8bee0 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"div1 c12\"><div class=\"fit\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\"><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005037\">[4]</$link> See note to <$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000004120\">v. 1599</$link> above.</div></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005057": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005057",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-0bfa64 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-e8bee0 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"div1 c12\"><div class=\"fit\"><div class=\"footnotes\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005058": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005058",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-0bfa64 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-e8bee0 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"div1 c12\"><div class=\"fit\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\"><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005043\">[5]</$link> This is perhaps the least understood sentence in the poem, almost every word being open to dispute. (1) The ‘<span class=\"ang\">nó</span>’ of our text is an emendation, and is rejected by many scholars. (2) ‘<span class=\"ang\">Seldan</span>’ is by some taken as an adv. (= <i>seldom</i>), and by others as a noun (= <i>page</i>, <i>companion</i>). (3) ‘<span class=\"ang\">Léod-hryre</span>,’ some render ‘<i>fall of the people</i>’; others, ‘<i>fall of the prince</i>.’ (4) ‘<span class=\"ang\">Búgeð</span>,’ most scholars regard as the intrans. verb meaning ‘<i>bend</i>,’ ‘<i>rest</i>’; but one great scholar has translated it ‘<i>shall kill</i>.’ (5) ‘<span class=\"ang\">Hwær</span>,’ Very recently, has been attacked, ‘<span class=\"ang\">wære</span>’ being suggested. (6) As a corollary to the above, the same critic proposes to drop ‘<span class=\"ang\">oft</span>’ out of the text.—t.B. suggests: <span class=\"ang\">Oft seldan wære</span> after <span class=\"ang\">léodhryre</span>: <span class=\"ang\">lýtle hwíle bongár búgeð, þéah séo brýd duge</span> = <i>often has a treaty been (thus) struck, after a prince had fallen: (but only) a short time is the spear (then) wont to rest, however excellent the bride may be</i>.</div></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005059": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005059",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-0bfa64 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-e8bee0 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"div1 c12\"><div class=\"fit\"><div class=\"footnotes\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
