        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005451": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005451",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-0bfa64 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-e8bee0 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"div1 c12\"><div class=\"fit\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\"><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005314\">[2]</$link> For ‘<span class=\"ang\">eafor</span>’ (2153), Kl. suggests ‘<span class=\"ang\">ealdor</span>.’ Translate then: <i>Bade the prince then to bear in the banner, battle-high helmet, etc</i>. On the other hand, W. takes ‘<span class=\"ang\">eaforhéafodsegn</span>’ as a compound, meaning ‘helmet’: <i>He bade them bear in the helmet, battle-high helm, gray armor, etc</i>.</div></div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005452": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005452",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-0bfa64 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-e8bee0 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"div1 c12\"><div class=\"fit\"><div class=\"footnotes\">\n</div></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005453": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005453",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-0bfa64 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-e8bee0 twpub-b444daeafa3e6711-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"div1 c12\"><div class=\"fit\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\"><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/b444daeafa3e6711/text/000005324\">[3]</$link> The H.-So. rendering (<span class=\"ang\">ærest</span> = <i>history, origin</i>; ‘<span class=\"ang\">eft</span>’ for ‘<span class=\"ang\">est</span>’), though liable to objection, is perhaps the best offered. ‘That I should very early tell thee of his favor, kindness’ sounds well; but ‘his’ is badly placed to limit ‘<span class=\"ang\">ést</span>.’—Perhaps, ‘<span class=\"ang\">eft</span>’ with verbs of saying may have the force of Lat. prefix ‘<span class=\"la\">re</span>,’ and the H.-So. reading mean, ‘that I should its origin rehearse to thee.’</div></div></div></div></div>"
        },
